            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XII.L5</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>To shew why, and how [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-338322df-7fff-9db2-6aa1-4684ac57a395\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While the length and elaboration of this note indicate some surety of purpose, the question marks suggest that Dickens was still uncertain about using Rigaud/Blandois in this manner. Dickens places heavy emphasis in this number on establishing Gowan&rsquo;s character, since doing so helps to deepen our sympathy for his wife Minnie (Pet) and justify Miss Wade&rsquo;s bitterness towards him in her future narrative (No. XVI). This memorandum establishes the basis for the opening chapter note for chapter 6, &ldquo;Anatomise Gowan, and see what breeds about his heart&rdquo; (LD.XII.R9).&nbsp;</p>"
        }
